 don't have much status.
 The status goods are used indicate higher status both by those who already
 have higher status and those who don't have higher status could appear
 problematic to the a modeler and the empiricist alike.
 As outlined by Veblen, conscpicuous consumption comprises both of individious
 comparison (IC) and pecuniary emulation (PE) (for which we use a general
 definition of status consumption).
 Thus the consumer both want to be like the rich and indicate that they
 are indeed richer than those not as rich as them.
 The modern view therefore considers the role of reference key to the notion
 of conspicuous consumption.
 Indeed the mechanisms of IC and PE are theoretical (normative) concerns
 as a consumer hardly knows the reason for such status good purchases.
 Instead the uncertainty towards each other's status is what drives conspicuous
 consumption.
 This is the view articulated as non-transactional choice by Maliath .
 The modern view of status consumption associates a particular context or
 reference with the status competitions where consumers participate with
 status items (see Frank).
 We associate this context with differences in income and wealth to understand
 how they could status consumption for the consumer.
