\begin_layout Standard
[INTERCHANGEABILITY Reference, TP] The role of interchangeability in status
 comparisons is key to the notion of status and competitions in the model.
 Every consumer gets utility from the absolute assets she has and the probabilit
y of having higher assets in future.
 While the former is encompassed by the total asset worth of the individual,
 the latter varies across asset bands since the transitional probability
 function can be different for every asset band.
 The consumers compare themselves with each other based on both assets and
 the probability.
 For consumer within the same asset-band, the role of assets is minimal
 and the only differences arise due to status consumption.
 For consumers in a different band asset-band identity dominates.
 A consumer in the low-asset band can never have a status higher than someone
 in the higher asset-band.
 This is problematic if you argue that status is more than wealth and that
 a consumer in a lower asset band should be allowed at least tecnically
 to have the same asset as someone in a higher band.
 Our model does allow assets to matter but it assumes that only assets matter
 beyond one's reference.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
[INTERCHANGEABILITY - NOT CLEAR] Interchangeability is crucial to the definition
 of asset bands as defined above.
 All status comparisons outside the band are strictly asset-based but within
 one's own reference, where occupational and social differences are few,
 both assets and future prospects matter.
 To consider an example, a classical musician might consider herself of
 higher status than the country musician- but the status differences between
 successful classical musicians and successful musicians could be driven
 by asset values.
 Our model only considers the importance of asset bands in such comparisons.
 In terms of the model, there are two possibilities when a classical musician
 compares herself with a country musician.
 First is when they both belong to the same asset-band and the second when
 they don't.
 When both the country musician and classical musician belong to the same
 asset-band, .
 they are are meant to make just about the same amount of money and musicians
 could compare themselves both on the net worth they achieve through labour
 and how prepared they are to be in the next asset-band e.g.
 with education and social networks.
 In fact the higher status for musicians of the classical genre is not without
 the role of a much longer history of elite patronage than for country music.
 Within the same reference i.e.
 for country musicians as well classical musicians the incomes are comparable.
 The other possibility is that most classical musicians are poorer than
 country musicians and they do not consider themselves interchangeable.
 In term of the model, while the private view of country musicians may consider
 country musicians to be of lower status, one would need enough classical
 musicians to become as rich as the country musician for there to be any
 comparable status utility between country and classical musicians.
\end_layout

